 Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Aldford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Aldford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Middlewich, Cheshire, England":"Middlewich, Cheshire, England","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Alderley, Cheshire, England":"Alderley, Cheshire, England","Weaver, Chester, England":"Weaver, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Arderne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Ardern  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ardern","meanings":["English: locative name variant of   Arden  . Arden in Cheshire is recorded as  <i>Arderne</i> in 1260, and Arden in Warwicks is recorded as  <i>Arderne</i> in 1200."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":42,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Arderne was born in 1340, in Alderley, Cheshire, England, her father, Peter de Arderne III, was 34 and her mother, Christiana, was 25. She married Richard de Weaver in 1369, in Middlewich, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1390, in Derbyshire, England, at the age of 50, and was buried in Derbyshire, England."},"et":{"1340–1390":"1340–1390","–Female":"Surnud","1328–1378":"1328–1378","1360–1399":"1360–1399","1377–Male":"1377–Surnud","1306–1348":"1306–1348","1315–1365":"1315–9.jaanuar1365kuni8.jaanuar1366","1352":"9. jaanuar 1352 kuni 8. jaanuar 1353","1340":"1340","1360":"1360","1382":"1382","1390":"1390","abt 1377":"umbes 1377","1348":"1348","1315"